You're right, when a team is on bye `nflgame` does a rather inelegant job at combining all of the plays for the games they played that week.

Your function kind of does a lot of things (generates games, combines the plays, finds all the sacks, and then writes data to a csv file), but you have some options on what to do here depending on how you want your CSV to note those bye weeks.

If you ultimately want your file to have 512 lines after an entire season (32 teams in the league that play 16 games each), then just `return` from your function if they didn't play any games during the week in question.

```python
def sacks(w, t):

    games = nflgame.games_gen(2016, w, t, t)

    if not games:
        return None

    plays = nflgame.combine_plays(games)

    sks = 0
        
    for p in plays.filter(team__ne=t):
        if p.defense_sk > 0:
            sks += 1
        else:
            sks += 0
    sackwriter.writerow([w, t, sks])
```

If instead you want your file to have 544 lines after a full season is completed (32 teams * 17 weeks), you could do something like this:
```python
def sacks(w, t):

    games = nflgame.games_gen(2016, w, t, t)

    sks = 0

    if games:
        plays = nflgame.combine_plays(games)
        for p in plays.filter(team__ne=t):
            if p.defense_sk > 0:
                sks += 1
            else:
                sks += 0
    sackwriter.writerow([w, t, sks])
```

